# System Architecture

## Overview

These architectural guidelines establish the foundational patterns and principles for building maintainable, scalable, and robust applications using TanStack Start.

## Related Guidelines

- [Principles](mdc:principles.mdc) - Core development principles
- [Standards](mdc:standards.mdc) - Code style and quality standards

## Core Architecture Principles

### 1. Separation of Concerns

- Divide the application into distinct features
- Separate business logic from UI components
- Keep data fetching logic isolated
- Maintain clear boundaries between layers
- Follow the single responsibility principle

### 2. Modularity

- Build small, focused modules
- Design for reusability
- Minimize dependencies between modules
- Use clear interfaces between components
- Implement proper encapsulation

### 3. Scalability

- Design for horizontal scaling
- Implement proper caching strategies
- Use efficient data loading patterns
- Optimize for performance
- Plan for future growth

## Application Structure

### Layer Separation

```sh
app/
├── components/             # UI Components
│   ├── ui/                # Reusable UI components
│   └── features/          # Feature-specific components
├── lib/                   # Core Logic
│   ├── client/           # Client-only code
│   ├── server/           # Server-only code
│   └── shared/           # Shared utilities
├── routes/                # Routing and Pages
│   ├── __root.tsx        # Root layout
│   ├── api/              # API endpoints
│   ├── _public/          # Public routes
│   ├── _auth/            # Auth routes
│   └── _app/             # Protected routes
└── types/                # Type definitions
```

### Feature Organization

```sh
features/
├── auth/                  # Authentication feature
│   ├── components/       # Auth-specific components
│   ├── lib/             # Auth business logic
│   └── types/           # Auth type definitions
└── users/                # Users feature
    ├── components/       # User-specific components
    ├── lib/             # User business logic
    └── types/           # User type definitions
```

## Data Flow Architecture

### 1. Server Functions

```typescript
// ✅ Good - Proper server function architecture
// lib/server/users.ts
export const $getUser = createServerFn({ method: 'GET' })
  .input(z.object({ id: z.string() }))
  .handler(async ({ input }) => {
    return db.user.findUnique({ where: { id: input.id } });
  });

// ❌ Bad - Mixed concerns
function UserProfile() {
  const $getUser = createServerFn({ method: 'GET' }); // Don't define here
  return <div>...</div>;
}
```

### 2. API Routes

```typescript
// ✅ Good - Clean API route architecture
// routes/api/auth/$.ts
export const APIRoute = createAPIFileRoute('/api/auth/$')({
  GET: ({ request }) => auth.handler(request),
  POST: ({ request }) => auth.handler(request),
});

// ❌ Bad - Mixed responsibilities
export const APIRoute = createAPIFileRoute('/api/mixed')({
  GET: ({ request }) => {
    // Auth, email, and other mixed logic
  },
});
```

## State Management Architecture

### 1. Global State

```typescript
// ✅ Good - Proper state architecture
// lib/client/store.ts
interface AppState {
  theme: 'light' | 'dark';
  user: User | null;
}

const useStore = create<AppState>()((set) => ({
  theme: 'light',
  user: null,
  setTheme: (theme) => set({ theme }),
  setUser: (user) => set({ user }),
}));

// ❌ Bad - Scattered state
const useTheme = create(() => ({ theme: 'light' }));
const useUser = create(() => ({ user: null }));
```

### 2. Server State

```typescript
// ✅ Good - Organized query architecture
// lib/client/queries/users.ts
export function useUser(id: string) {
  return useQuery({
    queryKey: ['user', id],
    queryFn: () => $getUser({ id }),
  });
}

// ❌ Bad - Inline queries
function UserProfile({ id }: { id: string }) {
  const { data } = useQuery({
    queryKey: ['user', id],
    queryFn: () => $getUser({ id }),
  });
}
```

## Component Architecture

### 1. Component Hierarchy

```typescript
// ✅ Good - Clear component hierarchy
// components/features/users/UserDashboard.tsx
function UserDashboard() {
  return (
    <DashboardLayout>
      <UserProfile />
      <UserActivity />
      <UserSettings />
    </DashboardLayout>
  );
}

// ❌ Bad - Flat structure
function UserDashboard() {
  return (
    <div>
      <Header />
      <Nav />
      <Profile />
      <Activity />
      <Settings />
      <Footer />
    </div>
  );
}
```

### 2. Component Composition

```typescript
// ✅ Good - Proper composition
function DataTable<T>({ data, columns, Toolbar }: DataTableProps<T>) {
  return (
    <div>
      <Toolbar />
      <Table data={data} columns={columns} />
    </div>
  );
}

// ❌ Bad - Rigid implementation
function DataTable<T>({ data, columns }: DataTableProps<T>) {
  return (
    <div>
      <DefaultToolbar /> {/* No flexibility */}
      <Table data={data} columns={columns} />
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Error Handling Architecture

### 1. Error Boundaries

```typescript
// ✅ Good - Proper error boundary architecture
// components/error-boundary.tsx
function ErrorBoundary({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<Loading />}>
      <ErrorBoundaryImpl>
        {children}
      </ErrorBoundaryImpl>
    </Suspense>
  );
}

// routes/dashboard/route.tsx
export const Route = createFileRoute('/dashboard')({
  component: DashboardPage,
  errorComponent: DashboardErrorBoundary,
});
```

### 2. Error Types

```typescript
// ✅ Good - Structured error architecture
// lib/shared/errors.ts
export class AppError extends Error {
  constructor(
    message: string,
    public code: string,
    public status: number,
    public cause?: unknown,
  ) {
    super(message);
  }
}
```
